        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                <placeName>Pha</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Norfolk</placeName>
                <date>April 22/66</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Esteemed Sir and Brother!</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><sic>Thankfull</sic> &amp;<lb/> obliged to you for the large amount
                of<lb/> attention paid unto me since late,<lb/> I beg to inform you, that on<lb/>
                request of the <placeName>Norfolk</placeName> Institute<lb/> I paid them a visit
                &amp; gave them<lb/> a lecture yesterday at their divine<lb/> service
                    (<add>hebrew</add>). As I hear acer-<lb/>tain <persName>Mr. or Dr
                    Bean</persName> residing in <placeName>N. York</placeName><lb/> &amp;
                recommended by <persName>Messrs Rev. <hi rend="underline"
                >Einhorn</hi></persName><lb/> &amp; <hi rend="underline"
                    ><persName>Adler</persName></hi>, <placeName>N.Y.</placeName>, is the other
                party,<lb/> I am to <sic>compede</sic> with. Do you,<lb/> esteemed Sir, know the
                party, is he<lb/> (<persName>Mr. Bean</persName>) not one of the <hi
                    rend="underline">very radical</hi> party?<lb/> If so, you would oblige me to the
                highest<lb/> degree by communicating such to the <placeName>Norfolk</placeName></p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Institute Board, but <hi rend="underline">without mentioning</hi>,<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">anything of this letter</hi>, being now certain<lb/> that your
                    <hi rend="underline">word</hi> has some great in-<lb/>fluence on the Norfolkers
                &amp; would make<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">big stroke</hi> through <hi
                    rend="underline"><persName>Mr Beans</persName>
                </hi>account.<lb/> So far as I see, I have a very good<lb/> chance, but <hi
                    rend="underline"><persName>Bean</persName></hi> has some patronizers<lb/> too,
                it would therefore be of great<lb/> advantage for my part, if you<lb/> would oblige
                me by complying with<lb/> the above. As the cause will be<lb/> decided on
                    <date>Saturday</date> next, your<lb/> letter would have to arrive here
                before<lb/> that time. Excuse, Sir, the lot of<lb/> trouble I have put unto you
                &amp; be<lb/> honored, that gratitude on my<lb/> part will always be my first<lb/>
                aim. Yours most obdt. servant</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">E L Hess</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <placeName>19 W. Balto St</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <placeName>Balto</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>P.S. <sic>Adress</sic> the letter</p>
            <p>
                <persName>J Hofheimer</persName>
            </p>
            <p>President of the <placeName>Norfolk</placeName> English &amp; Hebrew Institute</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <placeName>Norfolk Va</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>I will leave here tomorrow for <placeName>Balto</placeName>.</p>
